WEBVTT

00:11.714 --> 00:21.769
It's so great to be with you and I especially want to say welcome to any of you who maybe were visiting us with us last week at Easter for the first time and you've joined us again today.

00:21.789 --> 00:26.255
We gather together for worship and this is what we do now on Sundays.

00:26.535 --> 00:39.314
We have community group digital gatherings and now we have every week a 10, 30 larger public gatherings specifically for people who aren't in community groups or who are visiting and checking us out.

00:39.490 --> 00:43.677
And I want to be clear on this that gathering is so important for us as a church.

00:44.358 --> 00:52.751
I mean, we are a family of sinners saved by grace who gather for worship, scatter for mission, and do everything for the glory of God.

00:53.152 --> 00:56.317
And so we don't just want people watching the same content.

00:56.377 --> 01:01.785
We actually want to come together even if it's just digitally to worship the Lord.

01:02.166 --> 01:07.314
And so this is a time for us where we acknowledge that this isn't ideal.

01:07.426 --> 01:14.176
This isn't what we want to be doing or what we have been doing or what we will be doing in the long run, but this is what we've got right now.

01:14.356 --> 01:32.023
And so we want to come together digitally and we'll hold that tension of being able to be really grateful for technology in this time, but also lament the loss of physical presence of being able to give one another a hug, a greeting to hear each other's voices as we sing.

01:32.063 --> 01:36.530
But we'll continue to gather this way and look to the Lord as one people.

01:36.994 --> 01:41.721
One way that we worship as a church is through giving of our tides and our offerings.

01:42.262 --> 01:46.248
We want to be a generous people because we serve a generous God.

01:46.749 --> 01:52.097
And I know that this is a difficult time financially for so many people in our city and for many of you.

01:52.557 --> 01:58.366
I hope it's a time more than ever where the church steps up and we're helping out one another meeting each other's needs.

01:58.887 --> 02:03.794
But I also would want to encourage you and call you to continue to give to the church.

02:03.970 --> 02:07.554
The Lord has called us here and he's working in and through the church.

02:07.634 --> 02:09.676
Our staff is working hard.

02:09.736 --> 02:12.359
We're serving meals every day at the Hope Center.

02:12.439 --> 02:14.962
We're supporting organizations in our city.

02:15.523 --> 02:23.111
So we would ask that you would continue to give joyfully and sacrificially as the Lord works in and through us as a church.

02:24.012 --> 02:24.213
All right.

02:24.233 --> 02:29.198
We are starting a new sermon series today on the book of Philippians.

02:29.479 --> 02:32.562
And we're calling this series Defiant Joy.

02:33.122 --> 02:42.315
I really think that the book of Philippians is incredibly relevant for us today and everything that we're experiencing in this global pandemic.

02:42.335 --> 02:42.876
Think about it.

02:43.136 --> 02:49.826
In this letter that Paul writes to the church in Philippi, Paul is in prison, so talk about social distancing.

02:49.886 --> 02:51.729
He can certainly identify with us there.

02:52.169 --> 03:00.882
He's got a friend who is ill and he talks constantly about how whether he is present or absent, that they are to be faithful to the Lord.

03:01.218 --> 03:08.745
But more importantly, what we see throughout the book of Philippians is this call to press on even in the midst of adversity.

03:09.686 --> 03:11.087
We can have joy and suffering.

03:11.448 --> 03:13.830
We can experience community in isolation.

03:14.190 --> 03:16.733
We can have contentment even in hardship.

03:17.273 --> 03:24.800
That's why we're calling this series Defiant Joy because we refuse to let our circumstance have the final say over our lives.

03:25.241 --> 03:30.866
Jesus has the final say over our lives and we will find our joy and our peace and our contentment

03:30.946 --> 03:31.427
in him.

03:31.487 --> 03:46.235
Now as we go through this series on the book of Philippians, we're also going to have some weekly formative practices that we put out there for you all to be able to connect what you learn on Sundays with your daily life Monday through Saturday.

03:46.676 --> 03:51.986
So we'll be putting out some content early in the week through social media and our website.

03:52.130 --> 03:56.015
that's gonna help us put into practice what we're learning in the book of Philippians.

03:56.516 --> 04:08.432
In Philippians four verse, in chapter four verse nine, the Apostle Paul says, all these things that I'm teaching you and that you're hearing and that you're learning, practice them, do them, put them into practice.

04:08.452 --> 04:14.019
So we wanna work hard to do this as a church and be able to be connected throughout the week in that way.

04:14.780 --> 04:22.130
All right, in this first week of the series, I'm gonna be preaching on just the first two verses of the book, Philippians chapter one.

04:22.242 --> 04:27.407
verses one and two, so I'll read that for us and then I'll open our time in prayer.

04:28.708 --> 04:31.631
Philippians chapter one, verses one and two.

04:33.713 --> 04:36.436
Paul and Timothy, servants of Christ Jesus.

04:37.457 --> 04:47.967
To all the saints in Christ Jesus who are at Philippi, with the overseers and deacons, grace to you in peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.

04:48.608 --> 04:50.770
This is God's word, let's pray together.

04:54.434 --> 05:01.144
God, we come before you desperate for you to move, for you to intervene, for you to work in our lives.

05:01.805 --> 05:06.632
We long for the grace and peace that your scriptures speak of.

05:07.533 --> 05:14.504
God, we pray for grace and peace for the medical workers and first responders in our city and throughout this world.

05:15.345 --> 05:21.314
God, we pray for grace and peace for those who have lost work and who are hurting financially right now.

05:21.714 --> 05:24.178
We pray for grace and peace for the sick

05:24.450 --> 05:28.056
and for those who are grieving the loss of loved ones.

05:28.797 --> 05:39.093
We pray for grace and peace for us as a church and for other churches throughout Los Angeles, that this would be a time where we look to you, where we cry out to you, where we trust in you.

05:39.153 --> 05:52.594
And God, we pray that this would be a time where we grow, where we grow in our dependence on you, where we grow in our love for you, because you're giving us eyes to see how you're at work in all of this, Lord, we trust you.

05:53.026 --> 05:56.130
And we pray that you would work mightily today through the preaching of your word.

05:56.490 --> 05:57.872
We pray this in Jesus' name.

05:58.432 --> 05:58.733
Amen.

06:00.735 --> 06:01.155
Amen.

06:01.876 --> 06:08.364
Well, what we have in the book of Philippians is this letter that the Apostle Paul writes to a church in Philippi.

06:08.844 --> 06:13.890
Now, Philippi is this city that was a, it's in modern day Greece, but it was a Roman colony.

06:13.930 --> 06:20.498
And what that meant is for them to be declared a Roman colony is it gave them a lot more status, a lot more honor,

06:20.578 --> 06:29.953
but it also meant that they had more money and so that Rome would come in and build things for them, like a library, like pagan temples, like arenas or theaters.

06:30.153 --> 06:43.755
And so this Roman colony of Philippi was a metropolitan city, teeming with life and culture and diversity, but it wasn't an easy place to be a follower of Jesus.

06:44.596 --> 06:47.681
The church there would have been dealing with all kinds of adversity.

06:47.721 --> 06:48.402
You pick up

06:48.514 --> 06:57.305
clues of that throughout the book of Philippians that they were dealing with suffering, with persecution, even some division within their own church.

06:57.946 --> 07:09.239
And yet amidst this diversity, what you see in the book of Philippians is that they truly were a community of joy, solidarity, and resilience.

07:09.820 --> 07:11.883
They weren't crushed by adversity.

07:12.203 --> 07:14.906
They were being strengthened by their adversity.

07:15.687 --> 07:17.810
And what if that could be true of us

07:18.018 --> 07:18.599
as well.

07:19.520 --> 07:26.769
What if in this adversity that we're experiencing now, this hardship, this uncertainty, what if it actually strengthened us?

07:26.849 --> 07:29.111
What if it strengthened you more as a person?

07:29.452 --> 07:34.798
Well, I believe that that's exactly what can happen and what God wants to happen.

07:34.898 --> 07:41.266
So how did this church become a community of joy and solidarity and resilience?

07:41.570 --> 07:47.456
Well, to answer that question, I've got to give you a little bit of the backstory for this church in Philippi.

07:47.536 --> 07:50.440
And that comes from Acts chapter 16.

07:50.560 --> 07:59.629
So if you've got a Bible flipped there, I'm mostly going to summarize this, but I would love for you to be able to follow along and read this for yourself.

07:59.709 --> 08:01.371
So it starts with the Apostle Paul.

08:01.932 --> 08:11.442
He is like a missionary urban church planter who's going from city to city and planting churches as people's lives are being transformed by the gospel.

08:11.554 --> 08:14.137
He meets a young man named Timothy.

08:14.237 --> 08:18.622
Timothy has one of his parents who is a believer, the other is not.

08:19.022 --> 08:21.845
Paul becomes like a spiritual father to him.

08:21.905 --> 08:23.527
He takes him under his wing.

08:23.547 --> 08:29.274
And one day, Paul has this vision of a man of Macedonia.

08:29.474 --> 08:33.618
Now Macedonia is the region that the city of Philippi was in.

08:33.719 --> 08:40.466
And so this man of Macedonia presents himself to Paul in this vision, in this vision at night,

08:40.706 --> 08:49.956
And Paul walks away from this very clearly believing that God has called him to go to Macedonia and specifically to Philippi.

08:50.497 --> 08:54.301
And so Paul is on this journey as you read through the book of Acts.

08:54.321 --> 08:59.327
He goes from the Middle East to Asia Minor and then to modern day Europe.

08:59.707 --> 09:04.412
Philippi, in fact, is the first church plant in modern day Europe.

09:04.633 --> 09:09.458
And so I want you to hear that that Paul goes there because he's called by God.

09:10.050 --> 09:15.637
Now, if you ask what brought Paul to Philippi, well, at one level, the answer could be a sailboat.

09:15.877 --> 09:17.099
He had to sail there.

09:17.980 --> 09:22.345
But Paul would say, more ultimately, he was brought there by God.

09:22.505 --> 09:24.528
He was there because he was called by God.

09:24.928 --> 09:25.769
So let me ask you this.

09:26.430 --> 09:27.531
Why are you in Los Angeles?

09:27.972 --> 09:29.053
What brought you here?

09:29.594 --> 09:30.575
Maybe it was a 747.

09:31.556 --> 09:32.317
Maybe it was a car.

09:32.678 --> 09:33.579
Maybe it was your parents.

09:33.639 --> 09:34.700
Maybe it was a job.

09:34.760 --> 09:35.921
Maybe it was school.

09:35.962 --> 09:37.984
What brought you to Los Angeles?

09:38.044 --> 09:39.666
Well, what I want you to see here is

09:39.906 --> 09:43.590
with the Apostle Paul, it's true of us, God has called us here.

09:44.111 --> 09:46.634
He has greater purposes for us.

09:46.954 --> 09:52.100
And so Paul and Timothy and Silas and Luke, they go to Philippi.

09:52.580 --> 09:58.587
And when they go to Philippi, what Paul would traditionally do is he would go and find the synagogue and that's where he would start.

09:59.168 --> 10:01.010
But there was no synagogue there.

10:01.190 --> 10:08.018
And so he's looking around, he ends up outside of the city and stumbles upon a women's prayer meeting.

10:08.418 --> 10:16.858
And so he goes to this group of women who are praying outside of the city, and he starts telling them about Jesus, that he's the Messiah.

10:17.459 --> 10:20.366
And one of the women in this group, her name is Lydia.

10:21.068 --> 10:24.315
Now, Lydia is from a place originally called Thyatira.

10:24.335 --> 10:27.282
That means that ethnically she was Asian.

10:27.394 --> 10:30.219
But now she's living in the city of Philippi.

10:30.259 --> 10:33.385
We're told that she was a seller of purple goods.

10:33.745 --> 10:35.348
Now, purple die.

10:35.388 --> 10:37.452
It was very expensive in their time.

10:37.492 --> 10:41.619
And so that means that she's probably someone who is selling clothes.

10:41.659 --> 10:43.282
She's selling purple clothes.

10:43.623 --> 10:45.426
She would have been very wealthy.

10:45.506 --> 10:47.648
Lydia was a fashionista.

10:47.668 --> 10:56.017
If she was in LA, she would have gone to fit him and then opened her own clothing store down in the arts district or something like that.

10:56.477 --> 10:57.739
So she's a businesswoman.

10:58.199 --> 10:59.180
She's wealthy.

10:59.220 --> 11:02.123
And we're told that she is a God worshipper.

11:02.664 --> 11:12.914
Now, what that means is that she wasn't Jewish, but that she had stopped believing in all of the pagan gods, all of the Greek gods and the Roman gods.

11:13.058 --> 11:17.385
and that she believed in the one God that the Jews believed in.

11:17.946 --> 11:21.251
But she didn't yet believe that Jesus was the Messiah.

11:21.511 --> 11:25.177
And so Lydia and these women are there in this prayer meeting.

11:25.217 --> 11:27.381
The Apostle Paul shows up.

11:27.601 --> 11:33.871
This is how it all starts in Philippi, a women's prayer meeting and the Apostle Paul shows up and starts preaching the gospel to them.

11:33.911 --> 11:40.722
And it says that while Paul is preaching that the Lord opens up Lydia's heart.

11:41.282 --> 11:43.405
to pay attention to what's being said.

11:43.465 --> 11:46.108
She hears the good news of Jesus.

11:46.348 --> 11:54.879
She hears that he is the fulfillment of everything from the Old Testament, that he is the sacrifice for her sins, that he died, that he rose from the grave.

11:55.259 --> 11:59.564
She trusts in him and she becomes a follower of Jesus.

12:00.586 --> 12:02.208
So then she's a wealthy woman.

12:02.288 --> 12:03.710
She has her own home.

12:03.770 --> 12:07.855
She immediately then invites everyone back into her home.

12:07.915 --> 12:10.578
Now we're told from there

12:11.042 --> 12:20.112
that the Apostle Paul and his crew, they're walking along and this slave girl comes along and starts heckling them.

12:20.752 --> 12:22.234
So it's this young girl.

12:22.294 --> 12:23.996
She's literally a slave.

12:24.076 --> 12:28.100
She's someone, she's considered someone else's property basically.

12:28.641 --> 12:40.754
And what we're told about this slave girl is that she was demonized, that she was being oppressed by demons and that her owners were using her as a fortune teller.

12:41.154 --> 12:48.345
So there's these evil powers within her and they're using that to make money off of her as a fortune teller.

12:48.906 --> 13:00.222
Now this slave girl starts following around the Apostle Paul and everywhere, everywhere he goes, she follows them around and it's, she's following them.

13:00.263 --> 13:07.954
It's almost like she's heckling them, but what she's saying is she's saying, these men are servants of the Most High God who proclaim to you the way of salvation.

13:08.322 --> 13:11.867
So that's true what she's saying, but she won't leave them alone.

13:12.288 --> 13:16.954
For days she follows them or she's like a troll on Twitter, but Paul can't block her.

13:17.014 --> 13:20.459
Like she just keeps heckling them everywhere they go.

13:20.559 --> 13:24.725
And so it's remarkable what happens after many days of this.

13:25.286 --> 13:28.210
It says that Paul becomes so annoyed.

13:28.514 --> 13:28.834
Okay?

13:29.115 --> 13:37.624
You're not going to hear in very many miracles or exorcisms or anything like that in the Bible that come from a place of annoyance, but that's exactly what happens here.

13:38.104 --> 13:49.597
It says that Paul is so annoyed that he turns and says to this evil spirit, I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her and it came out that very hour.

13:50.558 --> 13:54.482
And so you could only imagine the peace and the joy

13:54.978 --> 14:00.564
that this slave girl must have experienced having this demon gone from her life.

14:01.505 --> 14:03.647
But the story takes a turn then.

14:03.687 --> 14:05.889
We don't hear much more about the slave girl.

14:05.949 --> 14:10.914
What we find out next is that the owners of the slave girl are livid.

14:11.455 --> 14:17.601
They're upset because this slave girl and her fortune telling was the way that they made money.

14:17.641 --> 14:22.386
And now that this evil spirit is gone, that they can't do that anymore.

14:22.914 --> 14:25.237
And so they go and they take the Apostle Paul.

14:25.677 --> 14:31.043
They drag him before the rulers in the city and they say, he's disrupting the city.

14:31.083 --> 14:32.685
He's ruining everything.

14:32.725 --> 14:34.127
They drag him before.

14:34.427 --> 14:39.093
And what happens is not just a couple of people accusing the Apostle Paul.

14:39.573 --> 14:44.119
It turns into a mob and they literally start beating Paul.

14:44.659 --> 14:46.822
They strip him of his clothes.

14:47.162 --> 14:50.546
They're striking him with long wooden sticks.

14:50.690 --> 15:03.469
It literally turns into this mob on the Apostle Paul and they take him after that, after he's beaten, he's naked, he's bloody, and they tell a, they tell a jailer, take him and put him in prison.

15:04.351 --> 15:07.876
So the jailer takes him, puts him in prison.

15:07.896 --> 15:17.010
And, and at that point you think, what's going to happen here is the Apostle Paul and, and, and Silas and those who are, are they even going to live through this?

15:17.666 --> 15:26.839
And the next thing that we hear in the story in Acts 16 is that at midnight, the apostle Paul and Silas are singing hymns and praying.

15:26.879 --> 15:29.402
They're in prison and they're singing.

15:29.522 --> 15:35.430
And not only are they singing, it says that the guards, the jailers are listening to them.

15:35.991 --> 15:36.652
Can you imagine that?

15:36.672 --> 15:40.017
They just finished beating them up and they're singing.

15:40.377 --> 15:44.282
Maybe the jailers were looking at one another and saying, you punched him in the mouth.

15:44.343 --> 15:46.866
And now he's using his mouth to sing praises.

15:46.946 --> 15:49.308
to his God, what is happening right now?

15:50.249 --> 15:57.556
And as they're singing and as the jailer is listening to them sing, we're told that a mighty earthquake comes.

15:58.257 --> 16:08.107
And with this earthquake that Paul and others, their chains are broken and they have the opportunity where they could run out and the jailer sees what's going on.

16:08.768 --> 16:12.531
And he knows if they get out on his watch that he will be killed.

16:13.392 --> 16:15.314
So he grabs his sword

16:15.554 --> 16:22.885
and points it towards himself and is getting ready to take his own life when the Apostle Paul cries out and says, stop, don't do it.

16:23.786 --> 16:31.737
And rather than them leaving prison when they have this opportunity, they take the opportunity to share the gospel with the jailer.

16:32.759 --> 16:36.544
And the jailer hears this and he says, what must I do to be saved?

16:37.666 --> 16:43.154
And so as they preach the word to him, he trusts in Christ for salvation,

16:43.266 --> 16:48.695
He's baptized along with his whole family, and then they go on from there.

16:48.755 --> 16:58.911
And so what I want you to hear from this crazy story in Acts 16 is think about the three different people that we heard about in the founding of this church.

16:59.893 --> 17:05.842
You've got an upper class woman, a middle class man, and a lower class girl.

17:07.104 --> 17:10.770
One of them is Asian, one's Greek, and the other is Roman.

17:11.426 --> 17:14.512
One was converted through reason and dialogue.

17:15.073 --> 17:18.039
One's converted through deliverance of an evil spirit.

17:18.500 --> 17:23.650
And one is converted after hearing the witness after an incredible miracle.

17:24.792 --> 17:29.741
So you've got this woman, this man, and this young girl.

17:29.761 --> 17:34.290
And that's the beginning of the church in Philippi.

17:34.882 --> 17:42.072
the gospel, changing lives and bringing people together who would otherwise have nothing to do with one another.

17:42.553 --> 17:59.417
All of a sudden they're this family centered on Christ and they grow into a church over the years that becomes healthy and even strong enough and substantial enough to be the primary people supporting Paul's missionary journeys.

18:00.598 --> 18:03.282
So we learned this in Philippians 4.

18:03.554 --> 18:09.763
that this church in Philippi would take up an offering and that they would support Paul so that he could go.

18:09.823 --> 18:20.638
So Paul leaves Philippi after starting this church there and he goes to Thessalonica and to Athens and to Corinth and to these major urban centers like Ephesus.

18:21.540 --> 18:25.746
And then eventually he's arrested again and he ends up in Rome in prison.

18:26.787 --> 18:28.690
And while he's in Rome in prison,

18:29.122 --> 18:35.392
He writes this letter back to the church in Philippi, probably 10 or 11 years later.

18:36.694 --> 18:51.216
And so the way that he introduces this letter, these first two verses that we're looking at today, it tells us so much about Paul, it tells us so much about the church in Philippi, and it can tell us so much about ourselves as well.

18:52.057 --> 18:57.906
So look back at verse one in Philippians chapter

18:58.530 --> 18:58.970
one.

19:00.092 --> 19:04.997
It simply begins Paul and Timothy, servants of Christ Jesus.

19:05.878 --> 19:07.499
Now Paul's introducing himself.

19:07.559 --> 19:09.541
That's the way they would do this in ancient letters.

19:10.222 --> 19:11.683
He would say his name first.

19:12.444 --> 19:14.947
But think about the way that he identifies himself.

19:16.028 --> 19:17.249
This is the apostle Paul.

19:17.810 --> 19:19.011
He planted that church.

19:19.371 --> 19:20.312
He's an apostle.

19:20.372 --> 19:22.374
He's traveled all these cities.

19:22.715 --> 19:23.796
He's well known.

19:24.156 --> 19:25.938
He wrote half the New Testament.

19:26.274 --> 19:33.941
He could introduce himself in so many ways, Paul, an apostle of Christ, Paul, the one who planted that church, Paul, the one who you owe your life to.

19:34.682 --> 19:38.606
No, he says, Paul, servant, servant of Jesus.

19:39.327 --> 19:42.009
That's how he sees his identity.

19:42.390 --> 19:46.814
He then goes on in verse two to declare their identity over them.

19:46.854 --> 19:52.499
Says to all the saints in Christ Jesus, isn't that beautiful?

19:53.320 --> 19:55.282
I mean, think back to who they were.

19:56.098 --> 20:02.944
a business woman who was probably caught up in everything involving her work.

20:02.964 --> 20:06.928
A middle class jailer who was doing his job, going to the jail every day.

20:07.008 --> 20:11.773
This young girl who was demonized and yet what does he say to them?

20:11.913 --> 20:12.513
Your saints.

20:13.795 --> 20:19.340
Now a saint in the Bible isn't someone who died long ago who's revered today.

20:19.400 --> 20:21.582
Now a saint is a Christian.

20:22.183 --> 20:25.906
The word saint literally means ones who are made holy

20:26.562 --> 20:29.085
He's reminding them of who they are in Christ.

20:29.406 --> 20:43.364
He says, remember who you were, you were selfish, you were prideful, you were slaves to sin, you were alone, but now in Christ, you're saints, you're holy, you're children of God, you're salt, you're light.

20:44.406 --> 20:53.618
And I love that he says to them, to all the saints in Christ Jesus who are at Philippi with the overseers and deacons.

20:53.890 --> 20:58.035
He specifically mentions church leadership here, overseers and deacons.

20:58.236 --> 21:07.808
And this is the pattern of what we see in the New Testament, that the church should be led by a plurality of elders, overseers, those words are used synonymously, and deacons.

21:08.549 --> 21:14.517
That's what we have at reality LA, we have elders and deacons, and then we have community group leaders.

21:15.458 --> 21:21.906
And just a few weeks ago when we were kind of initially adjusting to everything with the coronavirus,

21:22.178 --> 21:31.632
We did a Zoom call with a bunch of our elders and deacons and we had over a hundred of our community group leaders on the Zoom call and, and, and, at the Zoom meeting.

21:31.712 --> 21:37.401
And I, I told them, I said, listen, there's no way that we could prepare for what we're experiencing right now.

21:37.441 --> 21:38.923
This is totally unprecedented.

21:38.943 --> 21:41.126
It's obviously unexpected.

21:41.146 --> 21:49.138
I said, and yet, although there's no way that we could prepare, I said, I feel like we're as prepared for this as we could be because

21:49.538 --> 22:00.410
We have healthy leadership structures, biblical leadership structures, and we have incredible leaders, elders and deacons and community group leaders and people serving in a variety of different ways.

22:01.111 --> 22:03.633
And that is so important for the health of the church.

22:03.713 --> 22:05.796
It's important for us now as a church.

22:05.996 --> 22:18.930
And I'm grateful as I hear stories of the ways that our elders and deacons are reaching out and serving and shepherding and being connected as much as we possibly can in a time where that is difficult.

22:19.650 --> 22:27.279
He goes on in verse two then to simply say, Grace to you and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.

22:28.119 --> 22:29.521
Grace and peace.

22:30.402 --> 22:32.064
Those are the bookends of the gospel.

22:32.304 --> 22:35.187
And it's really a summary of the book of Philippians.

22:36.329 --> 22:39.332
Grace is the means and peace is the result.

22:40.413 --> 22:48.242
And we're gonna see so much of the depths of the gospel as we go through the book of Philippians over the next 15 weeks.

22:48.770 --> 22:52.714
But what I want to show you in the rest of our time today is a bit of an overview.

22:52.734 --> 23:01.743
I want to show you how through the book of Philippians, we'll see that the gospel creates a community of joy, solidarity and resilience.

23:02.404 --> 23:05.487
That's exactly what we need in the midst of this time.

23:05.968 --> 23:09.651
So first the gospel creates a community of joy.

23:10.252 --> 23:11.874
Philippian talks about joy a lot.

23:11.914 --> 23:16.018
In fact, 12 times it mentions the word joy or rejoice.

23:16.546 --> 23:18.849
But listen, this isn't a cheap joy.

23:18.889 --> 23:31.724
This isn't an attempt to downplay or minimize the actual hardships that we're going through today, nor was that Paul's intention with the people in Philippi then.

23:32.305 --> 23:33.867
This is a deep joy.

23:33.907 --> 23:37.131
This is a joy that we can have in suffering.

23:37.171 --> 23:39.474
This is a joy that's beyond circumstances.

23:39.794 --> 23:42.317
And we can have that because it's a joy from God.

23:43.178 --> 23:46.162
See, joy is not merely a feeling of happiness.

23:46.818 --> 23:53.686
Joy is a delight that is settled in your soul because it's based on something greater than your circumstances.

23:54.627 --> 24:07.142
I think about in the Old Testament, when God's people were in exile and they were afraid and their city had been demolished, what could Nehemiah tell his people to put strength in him?

24:07.943 --> 24:10.226
He said, the joy of the Lord is your strength.

24:10.690 --> 24:16.358
That's the kind of gospel rooted joy that we're going to be learning about through the book of Philippians.

24:16.799 --> 24:24.811
And I want you to know in the midst of all of this, in isolation and difficulty and loss, you can have joy.

24:24.871 --> 24:31.801
You can have joy that's from the Lord and that transcends the circumstances that we're in right now.

24:32.041 --> 24:37.970
So the gospel creates a community of joy and the gospel creates a community of solidarity.

24:38.530 --> 24:42.535
Now that word solidarity really means agreement, mutuality.

24:42.575 --> 24:46.921
It's a togetherness that comes from having a common interest.

24:47.882 --> 24:55.833
And it's amazing that this is such a prominent theme in the book of Philippians because the guy who's writing it is in prison.

24:57.095 --> 25:01.160
But think about this, Philippians, what we have is the book of Philippians.

25:01.661 --> 25:02.261
It's a letter.

25:03.083 --> 25:05.746
It was technology that Paul was using

25:06.082 --> 25:08.746
in place of face-to-face interaction.

25:09.247 --> 25:10.248
Sounds familiar, right?

25:11.110 --> 25:12.432
So he writes this letter.

25:13.313 --> 25:19.823
And even though he's in prison and they're far away, this letter is filled with language of deep relationships.

25:19.863 --> 25:22.947
He talks about how they have a partnership in the gospel.

25:23.528 --> 25:26.473
He talks about how together they are partakers of grace.

25:27.274 --> 25:30.839
He refers to people as fellow workers, fellow soldiers.

25:31.440 --> 25:32.722
And in chapter one verse eight,

25:33.218 --> 25:37.345
He says, I yearn for you with the affection of Jesus.

25:38.346 --> 25:47.241
So there's this deep longing for relationships and deep joy in the relationships that he has, even though they can't be together physically.

25:47.962 --> 25:50.526
Now, I think this is really applicable for us as a church.

25:51.928 --> 25:54.713
Think about back to the beginning of the year, Vision Sunday.

25:55.234 --> 26:00.402
We talked about how what we really believe, what God wants for us as a church this year,

26:00.834 --> 26:04.920
is that we would be a unified people in a fragmented culture.

26:06.041 --> 26:13.651
And we talked about that primarily in terms of politics and how there's gonna be so much division and people being torn apart in the midst of this year.

26:13.671 --> 26:16.515
We had no idea what was coming our way, right?

26:17.056 --> 26:21.522
And so at one level, we could look back to that and say, oh, I guess we were off or we didn't see what was coming.

26:21.542 --> 26:28.812
No, I think actually now we need to hear that word more than ever of what it means for us to be a unified people.

26:29.453 --> 26:30.514
Who would have thought

26:30.722 --> 26:35.567
that there would have been something that could pull people apart more than politics in the year 2020.

26:35.928 --> 26:40.152
And yet here we are forced to not come together physically.

26:40.953 --> 26:46.219
God is calling us and he wants to teach us through this time to be a unified people.

26:46.279 --> 26:47.981
We'll see that throughout the book of Philippians.

26:48.782 --> 26:52.366
So the gospel creates a community of joy and of solidarity.

26:53.047 --> 26:59.634
And then third, a community of resilience amidst the adversity that Paul speaks into.

27:00.034 --> 27:05.020
He pleads with them, hold fast, stand firm, press on.

27:05.921 --> 27:11.286
We need to be able to recognize that we can be strengthened by adversity.

27:11.347 --> 27:13.589
We don't have to be crushed by it.

27:14.410 --> 27:22.359
We need to be able to see through the lens of faith that every obstacle brings different opportunities with it and we can get creative about that.

27:23.200 --> 27:28.946
And this is what you see when you look back through the Scriptures and throughout church history.

27:29.250 --> 27:31.754
that the church is a resilient people.

27:31.774 --> 27:40.086
I mean, you see this with the Apostle Paul, he was shipwrecked, he was beaten, he was whipped, he was stoned.

27:40.246 --> 27:43.391
He just keeps getting back up and going back in and preaching the gospel.

27:43.971 --> 27:51.282
He has this mentality of the more you knock me down, the more I'll get up because I've got the Lord working in me and through me.

27:51.650 --> 27:58.021
You see this in the book of Acts, you see it in the early church where persecution spreads the church and it becomes mission.

27:58.561 --> 28:07.076
You see it throughout history that kingdoms come and go, movements rise and fall, but the church remains in the midst of all of that.

28:07.777 --> 28:12.505
We're gonna see throughout the book of Philippians that the mission of Jesus is unstoppable.

28:12.825 --> 28:14.368
Not because of us, but because of him.

28:14.408 --> 28:18.194
Nothing can stop God's purposes, not disease.

28:18.306 --> 28:22.230
Not persecution, not chains, not the devil, nothing.

28:23.751 --> 28:27.795
And all of this, again, is it's not because of our effort or who we are.

28:27.815 --> 28:29.877
It's because of God's grace.

28:29.897 --> 28:40.847
In Philippians 1, 6, the Apostle Paul says, and I am sure of this, that he who began a good work in you will bring it to completion at the day of Jesus Christ.

28:42.048 --> 28:44.010
God's going to finish the work that he has begun.

28:44.691 --> 28:47.954
So I want to encourage you, don't give up, endure,

28:48.290 --> 28:51.994
Hold fast, stand firm, press on.

28:52.335 --> 28:54.397
God is at work in all of this.

28:56.059 --> 28:59.943
Joy, solidarity, resilience.

29:01.505 --> 29:06.450
How can all of those things come from a man who's in prison?

29:06.971 --> 29:07.732
Well, I'll tell you why.

29:08.633 --> 29:13.458
Because he's pointing us to a savior who brought redemption through sacrifice.

29:14.498 --> 29:20.787
through the most horrific and ugly circumstance brought beauty and glory and salvation.

29:22.049 --> 29:22.630
Think about this.

29:22.690 --> 29:27.416
We're just looking at these first two verses in Philippians this week and it talks about a lot of things.

29:27.497 --> 29:36.229
Paul and Timothy and the saints and Philippi and overseers and deacons, but there's one word that it mentions three times here.

29:37.250 --> 29:42.578
Three times it mentions Jesus in these first two verses.

29:43.394 --> 29:49.703
When you talk about what the book of Philippians is all about and what's the theme of Philippians, let's not over-complicate this.

29:50.203 --> 29:50.824
It's Jesus.

29:51.625 --> 29:55.230
And it's when we look to Jesus ultimately that we have that joy.

29:55.470 --> 29:59.095
It's when we look to Jesus that we experience that solidarity that comes in community.

29:59.436 --> 30:04.082
It's when we look to Jesus that we have the kind of resilience that we need in a time like this.

30:04.983 --> 30:12.754
And this Jesus who we're gonna learn about in the book of Philippians is the one who is God himself, the king of the universe.

30:13.154 --> 30:17.220
who like it talks about in Philippians 2, took on the form of a servant.

30:17.941 --> 30:27.897
He humbled himself, even to death, to death on a cross, for us, for our sins, to make us new.

30:27.917 --> 30:32.664
But not only did he humble himself to death on a cross, he rose from the grave.

30:32.985 --> 30:35.248
He was highly exalted.

30:35.268 --> 30:38.994
He has a name above every name.

30:39.426 --> 30:47.516
And that name will be proclaimed so that every knee will bow and every tongue confess that Jesus is Lord.

30:48.357 --> 31:09.362
So church, I want to call you today to look to Christ, to keep your eyes fixed on Him, to not allow your circumstances, to determine your heart, to determine your joy, to determine your attitude, but to look to Christ and know that we have been given everything that we need in Him.

31:09.730 --> 31:11.633
And as we look to Christ, we'll do that together.

31:12.134 --> 31:17.862
This will be a time for us to rally as a church, to be strengthened by this adversity for the glory of God.

31:18.303 --> 31:19.004
Let's pray together.

31:21.027 --> 31:24.953
Jesus, we look to you as the crucified and resurrected one.

31:26.255 --> 31:39.314
And I pray for every single person listening to this right now, that as they look to you, that hope would rise in their hearts, that joy would spring up in their soul

31:40.098 --> 31:42.642
and that peace would settle deep within them.

31:43.743 --> 31:50.352
God, we pray for us as a church, that this would be a time where we are strengthened through adversity.

31:51.113 --> 32:02.950
God, throughout this series over the months to come, we pray that this would be a time where you cultivate deeper love in us for you and for one another and for our city.

32:03.291 --> 32:05.714
We pray this in Jesus' name, amen.

